&lt;/div>&lt;p>Because the interger in OCaml is &lt;code>OCamlnum == realnum * 2 + 1&lt;/code>, The &lt;code>leaq -1(%rax,%rbx), %rax&lt;/code> in &lt;code>camlExample.fun_342&lt;/code> is doing a plus operation. It&amp;rsquo;s my &lt;code>(fun acc x -&amp;gt; acc + x)&lt;/code>.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>At &lt;a class="link" href="https://ocaml.org/docs/compiler-backend#the-impact-of-polymorphic-comparison" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>here the official doc&lt;/a> said &lt;code>%r15&lt;/code> is used as a heap pointer in my case:&lt;br>
&lt;code>OCaml on x86_64 architectures caches the location of the minor heap in the %r15 register since it's so frequently referenced in OCaml functions.&lt;/code>&lt;/p>
&lt;p>It&amp;rsquo;s amazing that there&amp;rsquo;s two ways to curry a function. The first is the &lt;code>camlExample.4&lt;/code>, use a built-in function to curry my lambda function. Another is to build a sequence for a expression, and evaluate it.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>